  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why would I get a certified letter from the IRS?",
  "response": "Receiving a certified letter from the IRS can be concerning, but there are several reasons why the IRS might send one. Here are a few common possibilities:\n\n1. **Notification of Audit**: The IRS may notify you that your tax return is being audited. The certified letter will provide details about the audit process and what information you need to provide.\n\n2. **Balance Due**: If you owe taxes, the IRS may send a certified letter to inform you of the amount due and potential penalties and interest if payment is not made by a certain date.\n\n3. **Verification of Identity or Information**: The IRS may need to verify your identity or certain information related to your tax return. This could be due to suspected identity theft or discrepancies in the information provided.\n\n4. **Notice of Deficiency**: This indicates that the IRS has calculated that you owe additional taxes. The letter will provide details on the amounts and your rights to dispute the deficiency.\n\n5. **Proposed Changes to Your Return**: The IRS may propose changes to your tax return based on their review. The letter will explain the proposed changes and provide options for you to agree or contest them.\n\n6. **Collection Actions**: If you have unpaid taxes and have not responded to previous notices, the IRS might send a certified letter indicating the initiation of collection actions like liens or levies.\n\n7. **Tax Lien or Levy**: If the IRS intends to place a lien on your property or levy your bank account or wages, you will receive a certified notice explaining what actions will be taken and what you can do to address the situation.\n\n8. **Missing Documents**: The IRS might request additional documentation or clarification regarding your tax returns.\n\nIt's important to carefully read the letter and take timely action as indicated. Certified letters require your signature upon receipt, which serves as proof that you received the communication. If you are unsure why you received a certified letter, contact the IRS or a tax professional for assistance.",
